WEBVTT

00:04.415 --> 00:06.292
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:06.292 --> 00:08.410
<i>announcer: Tonight,</i>
<i>it's trial by fire</i>

00:08.410 --> 00:09.976
<i>as five fledgling forgers</i>

00:09.976 --> 00:11.959
<i>must earn their</i>
<i>right to compete.</i>

00:11.959 --> 00:14.629
- We asked you to forge
your best work for us to test

00:14.629 --> 00:16.505
before you even got here.

00:16.505 --> 00:18.716
You will have to earn
your spot at the anvil.

00:18.716 --> 00:21.052
And one of you
will be eliminated

00:21.052 --> 00:22.762
before we ever light
the first forge.

00:22.762 --> 00:24.096
<i>announcer:</i>
<i>Will these aspiring smiths</i>

00:24.096 --> 00:25.389
<i>crack under the pressure?</i>

00:25.389 --> 00:27.058
- I'm really very nervous.

00:27.058 --> 00:29.310
<i>announcer:</i>
<i>Or will they prove</i>

00:29.310 --> 00:31.354
<i>that they have the skills</i>
<i>to be one of the world's best,</i>

00:31.354 --> 00:35.983
<i>win $10,000, and be crowned</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion?</i>

00:35.983 --> 00:38.945
<i>[epic music]</i>

00:38.945 --> 00:44.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:44.408 --> 00:45.534
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:45.534 --> 00:47.078
<i>- My name is Joey Lynn.</i>

00:47.078 --> 00:48.162
And I've been watching
"Forged in Fire"

00:48.162 --> 00:49.872
since the beginning.

00:49.872 --> 00:51.832
<i>What inspired me</i>
<i>to make blades was</i>

00:51.832 --> 00:54.377
I was on vacation
in Pigeon Forge, Tennessee,

00:54.377 --> 00:56.712
and I came up
on Robbie Bowman's shop.

00:56.712 --> 00:59.090
<i>He was a two-time</i>
<i>competitor on the show.</i>

00:59.090 --> 01:01.467
<i>And I had the opportunity</i>
<i>to make a knife with him</i>

01:01.467 --> 01:03.594
and figured,
shoot, I can do this.

01:03.594 --> 01:05.721
So I went home, put me together
a forge, started pounding.

01:05.721 --> 01:07.682
<i>- My name is Tyler Grant.</i>

01:07.682 --> 01:10.017
I started making knives
when I was 12 years old

01:10.017 --> 01:13.062
<i>up till I was</i>
<i>around 15 years old.</i>

01:13.062 --> 01:16.023
And I started making
knives again because

01:16.023 --> 01:18.484
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>sparked my interest.</i>

01:18.484 --> 01:20.903
<i>I'm really confident</i>
<i>in my skills.</i>

01:20.903 --> 01:24.407
I think I could actually
go up against the power hammer.

01:24.407 --> 01:26.033
<i>- My name is Matt Wagner.</i>

01:26.033 --> 01:28.619
<i>I run an auto body</i>
<i>restoration shop</i>

01:28.619 --> 01:30.538
<i>and I work</i>
<i>with metal every day.</i>

01:30.538 --> 01:33.416
I started watching
"Forged in Fire,"

01:33.416 --> 01:35.042
<i>and then one day I was like,</i>
<i>you know what?</i>

01:35.042 --> 01:37.003
I think I can do that.

01:37.003 --> 01:38.838
<i>- My name is Brian Schmidt.</i>

01:38.838 --> 01:41.507
I believe my great grandfather
was a blacksmith.

01:41.507 --> 01:43.718
<i>So, when I saw</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire,"</i>

01:43.718 --> 01:46.178
<i>I wanted to try making</i>
<i>my own blades and just</i>

01:46.178 --> 01:48.097
create memories with my family.

01:48.097 --> 01:50.016
<i>- I am Steve Johnson.</i>

01:50.016 --> 01:52.101
<i>I got into making knives</i>
<i>because I'm a gunsmith.</i>

01:52.101 --> 01:53.978
And I looked around
the shop one day and said,

01:53.978 --> 01:55.646
I have the equipment.

01:55.646 --> 01:56.939
<i>I should try</i>
<i>making some knives.</i>

01:56.939 --> 01:58.566
<i>I first started making blades</i>

01:58.566 --> 02:00.359
<i>by stock removal.</i>

02:00.359 --> 02:02.153
And then I saw
"Forged in Fire" and I said,

02:02.153 --> 02:04.488
I have to try it like that.

02:04.488 --> 02:07.241
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

02:07.241 --> 02:09.452
We invited you here
to compete for the title of

02:09.452 --> 02:12.413
"Forged in Fire" champion
and $10,000 because

02:12.413 --> 02:14.832
each of you was inspired
to start smithing

02:14.832 --> 02:16.834
because of the show.

02:16.834 --> 02:20.171
For that reason, we've decided
to change things up.

02:20.171 --> 02:22.548
You're probably wondering
why there's five of you

02:22.548 --> 02:24.425
and only four anvils.

02:24.425 --> 02:26.427
That's because we're going
to start with a test

02:26.427 --> 02:28.846
on these blades
you've forged at home.

02:28.846 --> 02:30.681
We asked you
to forge your best work

02:30.681 --> 02:32.516
in the form of
a competition chopper

02:32.516 --> 02:34.602
between 8 and 12 inches
in length,

02:34.602 --> 02:36.395
not including the tang,

02:36.395 --> 02:38.856
with the overall length
not exceeding 15 inches.

02:38.856 --> 02:40.483
And they better be durable,

02:40.483 --> 02:42.068
because one of you
will be eliminated

02:42.068 --> 02:44.862
before we even
fire up the first forge.

02:44.862 --> 02:47.990
So, let's meet the men
testing and judging you.

02:47.990 --> 02:50.785
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion, Ben Abbott.

02:50.785 --> 02:53.412
Edged weapon specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:53.412 --> 02:56.832
Historic weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker.

02:56.832 --> 02:58.834
All right, let's go ahead
and get this party started.

02:58.834 --> 03:01.712
Up first,
is our qualifying test.

03:01.712 --> 03:04.340
Ben?

03:04.340 --> 03:06.801
- Bladesmiths, in this
sudden elimination round,

03:06.801 --> 03:08.469
I'll be smashing your knives

03:08.469 --> 03:11.013
into these blocks
of ice ten times.

03:11.013 --> 03:12.515
Steve, you're up first.
Are you ready?

03:12.515 --> 03:13.516
- Let's do it.

03:13.516 --> 03:14.475
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

03:14.475 --> 03:15.810
<i>It's a W2.</i>

03:15.810 --> 03:17.228
<i>It had to be a chopper,</i>

03:17.228 --> 03:19.355
<i>so I tried to design for that.</i>

03:19.355 --> 03:21.232
<i>Got some weight up front</i>

03:21.232 --> 03:22.650
<i>that'll hopefully</i>
<i>carry it through here.</i>

03:22.650 --> 03:23.776
<i>I think my blade will</i>

03:23.776 --> 03:26.529
destroy that ice.

03:26.529 --> 03:29.448
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:29.448 --> 03:36.372
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:37.998 --> 03:39.125
[metal clattering]

03:39.125 --> 03:40.126
- Oh.

03:40.126 --> 03:41.293
- [groans]

03:41.293 --> 03:44.255
<i>[tense music]</i>

03:44.255 --> 03:47.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:47.007 --> 03:48.425
- Well, Steve,

03:48.425 --> 03:49.385
we have a problem.

03:49.385 --> 03:51.095
- Yeah.

03:51.095 --> 03:53.139
- On the tenth strike,
the knife broke.

03:53.139 --> 03:55.891
That's because if you look
closely at this blade,

03:55.891 --> 03:58.394
you'll see that there's
a brown section of the crack.

03:58.394 --> 04:00.980
The brown section was
an old crack that happened

04:00.980 --> 04:02.731
probably in the quench.

04:02.731 --> 04:05.025
It's been there a while.
It's actually rusted.

04:05.025 --> 04:07.862
The rest of the edge
is still pretty sharp.

04:07.862 --> 04:11.615
But at the end of the day,
it did break.

04:11.615 --> 04:14.827
- Steve, that's what we call
a catastrophic blade failure

04:14.827 --> 04:16.537
and you all know
what that means.

04:16.537 --> 04:18.831
But, it's not over yet.

04:18.831 --> 04:22.042
Each of your blades must
survive all ten ice block chops

04:22.042 --> 04:23.919
in order to move forward.

04:23.919 --> 04:26.380
You guys will
be counting to ten

04:26.380 --> 04:29.341
like you never have
before in your life.

04:29.341 --> 04:31.051
- Well, Brian, you're up next.
Are you ready?

04:31.051 --> 04:32.052
- Let's do it.

04:32.052 --> 04:33.971
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:33.971 --> 04:35.389
<i>This is the longest blade</i>
<i>I've ever made.</i>

04:35.389 --> 04:37.600
<i>I've put a maple handle on it.</i>

04:37.600 --> 04:39.477
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>I'm nervous at all,</i>

04:39.477 --> 04:41.353
<i>I know that Steve's blade</i>
<i>just broke, but...</i>

04:41.353 --> 04:42.897
I know my blade's solid.

04:45.107 --> 04:48.068
<i>[rock music]</i>

04:48.068 --> 04:54.992
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:57.828 --> 05:00.706
<i>[tense music]</i>

05:00.706 --> 05:03.459
- Well, Brian,
your edge held up perfectly.

05:03.459 --> 05:05.753
It's like it never
even saw the ice.

05:05.753 --> 05:08.756
It's still like the minute
you brought it in.

05:08.756 --> 05:11.175
Got a nice finish to it.
It's got a great shape.

05:11.175 --> 05:12.176
Very well done.

05:12.176 --> 05:13.719
- Thank you.

05:13.719 --> 05:14.845
- Matt, you're up.
You ready?

05:14.845 --> 05:15.888
- I'm ready.

05:15.888 --> 05:17.139
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:17.139 --> 05:18.891
<i>I used a piece of W2.</i>

05:18.891 --> 05:21.310
<i>I made it short.</i>
<i>Robust. Strong.</i>

05:21.310 --> 05:22.853
<i>I think it feels good</i>
<i>in the hand,</i>

05:22.853 --> 05:24.480
<i>so I think</i>
<i>it's gonna do well.</i>

05:24.480 --> 05:25.606
<i>I hope.</i>

05:25.606 --> 05:28.567
<i>[rock music]</i>

05:28.567 --> 05:35.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:39.036 --> 05:40.621
- Nice.

05:40.621 --> 05:42.456
<i>[tense music]</i>

05:42.456 --> 05:44.959
- Well, Matt,
your knife held up very well.

05:44.959 --> 05:47.628
It's got a very thick edge.

05:47.628 --> 05:50.756
It's still sharp.
It's still in one piece.

05:50.756 --> 05:51.882
Well done.

05:51.882 --> 05:53.342
- Thank you.

05:53.342 --> 05:54.927
- Tyler, you're up.
You ready?

05:54.927 --> 05:56.637
- Swing it like you mean it.
- [laugh]

05:56.637 --> 05:57.888
<i>[tense music]</i>

05:57.888 --> 05:59.765
<i>- I made it out of W2.</i>

05:59.765 --> 06:02.393
<i>It may be the best blade</i>
<i>that I've ever made,</i>

06:02.393 --> 06:04.019
<i>but I just hope mine holds up</i>

06:04.019 --> 06:06.063
and I make it to ten.

06:06.063 --> 06:07.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:07.982 --> 06:10.943
<i>[rock music]</i>

06:10.943 --> 06:17.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:20.953 --> 06:22.496
<i>[tense music]</i>

06:22.496 --> 06:24.206
- Well, Tyler,

06:24.206 --> 06:25.874
this extreme curve
that you have here

06:25.874 --> 06:27.626
made it so that as
I was chopping the ice,

06:27.626 --> 06:29.169
I ended up hitting
my knuckle on the ice

06:29.169 --> 06:31.130
instead of the blade.

06:31.130 --> 06:33.173
But it held up.

06:33.173 --> 06:34.925
The edge is still sharp.

06:34.925 --> 06:35.968
Well done.

06:35.968 --> 06:37.428
- Thank you.

06:37.428 --> 06:38.971
- Joey, you're up.
You ready?

06:38.971 --> 06:40.931
- Let's get her done, brother.

06:40.931 --> 06:43.142
<i>I've never made</i>
<i>a competition chopper before,</i>

06:43.142 --> 06:44.893
<i>so I seen what one looked like</i>

06:44.893 --> 06:46.604
<i>and when I did my best</i>
<i>to recreate it.</i>

06:46.604 --> 06:48.355
<i>I'm really very nervous.</i>

06:48.355 --> 06:50.316
I'm hoping that
it's gonna do the job

06:50.316 --> 06:51.942
and survive through that chop.

06:53.777 --> 06:56.780
<i>[rock music]</i>

06:56.780 --> 07:03.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:04.997 --> 07:06.790
<i>[tense music]</i>

07:06.790 --> 07:09.376
- Well, Joey,
your edge held up perfectly.

07:09.376 --> 07:11.045
I like the shape of it.

07:11.045 --> 07:12.504
The weight of it--
it's a great chopper.

07:12.504 --> 07:14.673
Did some damage on the ice.

07:14.673 --> 07:15.883
Well done.

07:15.883 --> 07:17.259
- Thank you, sir.

07:17.259 --> 07:18.886
- Well, gentlemen,

07:18.886 --> 07:20.554
I don't think
that any bladesmith

07:20.554 --> 07:22.681
is really prepared
for the ice block chop

07:22.681 --> 07:24.767
and how devastating it can be.

07:24.767 --> 07:27.644
That being said,
Steve, because your blade

07:27.644 --> 07:30.189
suffered a catastrophic
weapons failure,

07:30.189 --> 07:33.192
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

07:33.192 --> 07:36.153
<i>- To get eliminated before</i>
<i>getting to work in The Forge</i>

07:36.153 --> 07:38.947
is really,
really disappointing.

07:38.947 --> 07:41.742
<i>But hopefully this</i>
<i>is just gonna take me</i>

07:41.742 --> 07:45.579
<i>to the next level</i>
<i>of being a better smith.</i>

07:45.579 --> 07:47.414
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.

07:47.414 --> 07:49.249
You all came here
with quality knives

07:49.249 --> 07:51.043
that passed through
our qualifying round.

07:51.043 --> 07:52.961
But the competition
is far from over.

07:52.961 --> 07:56.131
In an order chosen at random,
you will come forward

07:56.131 --> 07:58.884
and you will choose
one of these boxes.

07:58.884 --> 08:00.719
Brian, you're up first.

08:00.719 --> 08:02.012
Choose your box.

08:02.012 --> 08:04.098
- Hmm.

08:04.098 --> 08:06.433
- I've seen so many different
things on the show,

08:06.433 --> 08:08.268
so many different twists,

08:08.268 --> 08:10.646
<i>you know, anything could</i>
<i>be under that box.</i>

08:10.646 --> 08:15.150
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:16.276 --> 08:18.070
- Files.

08:18.070 --> 08:19.905
- Brian, you've chosen
the farrier files.

08:19.905 --> 08:21.448
<i>- What am I gonna</i>
<i>do with this?</i>

08:21.448 --> 08:23.325
I've never worked with rasp.

08:23.325 --> 08:25.452
<i>I think it's gonna</i>
<i>be difficult.</i>

08:25.452 --> 08:28.205
- Matt, you're up next.
Pick a box.

08:28.205 --> 08:31.792
<i>- I actually won $500 in</i>
<i>a challenge similar to this.</i>

08:31.792 --> 08:33.377
And I went up
and I smelled the box.

08:33.377 --> 08:35.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:35.254 --> 08:37.756
- [laughs]
- That's a good idea.

08:37.756 --> 08:38.924
- I'm right here.

08:38.924 --> 08:40.259
- All right.

08:40.259 --> 08:41.844
Show us what you got.

08:41.844 --> 08:43.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:43.846 --> 08:45.597
<i>Looks like you've got</i>
<i>some leaf springs.</i>

08:45.597 --> 08:48.142
- Maybe not my choice
of picks,

08:48.142 --> 08:50.894
<i>but spring steel</i>
<i>is a steel I've worked with</i>

08:50.894 --> 08:52.980
<i>and I know it's</i>
<i>something I can handle.</i>

08:52.980 --> 08:55.649
- Joey, you're up next.
Choose your box.

08:55.649 --> 09:02.614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:03.407 --> 09:04.950
- Oof.

09:04.950 --> 09:07.202
- [chuckles]
- Lawnmower blades.

09:07.202 --> 09:08.912
- Doggone lawnmower blades.

09:08.912 --> 09:10.748
<i>How am I gonna</i>
<i>close up the holes</i>

09:10.748 --> 09:13.667
in the blades here
to make another blade?

09:13.667 --> 09:15.502
My heart just sunk.

09:15.502 --> 09:17.921
- I'm next, I guess.
- [laughs]

09:17.921 --> 09:21.175
- I don't know
which one to choose.

09:21.175 --> 09:24.595
- Hey, what do you
think's under that box?

09:24.595 --> 09:25.888
- Metal.

09:25.888 --> 09:28.182
[laughter]

09:28.182 --> 09:29.683
<i>I don't care</i>
<i>what's in the box.</i>

09:29.683 --> 09:31.977
I think everybody
else is screwed.

09:31.977 --> 09:33.520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:33.520 --> 09:35.606
Oh, yeah.

09:35.606 --> 09:37.024
- Looks like you got yourself
a train spring there.

09:37.024 --> 09:39.276
- I got this in the bag now.

09:39.276 --> 09:42.362
<i>Only thing I gotta do</i>
<i>is figure out how much time</i>

09:42.362 --> 09:44.448
<i>it's gonna actually</i>
<i>take me to unravel this</i>

09:44.448 --> 09:46.450
thick piece of metal.

09:46.450 --> 09:48.452
- All right, bladesmiths,

09:48.452 --> 09:50.537
now that you have your steel,
you're gonna take that

09:50.537 --> 09:52.915
and you're gonna turn
it into a signature blade

09:52.915 --> 09:54.458
in your signature style

09:54.458 --> 09:56.210
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

09:56.210 --> 09:57.669
you'll be attaching
handles to those blades

09:57.669 --> 09:59.546
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

09:59.546 --> 10:01.381
that will be tested
for strength and durability

10:01.381 --> 10:06.386
in a bone chop and for
sharpness in a rope slice.

10:06.386 --> 10:08.430
There will be
no design period.

10:08.430 --> 10:10.849
But you will have
three hours in this round.

10:10.849 --> 10:12.559
Good luck, bladesmiths.

10:12.559 --> 10:16.104
Your time starts now.

10:16.104 --> 10:18.065
Ben, you're the only one
of these judges

10:18.065 --> 10:20.150
that has competed on this show.

10:20.150 --> 10:22.778
What made you think
that you could compete?

10:22.778 --> 10:24.279
- They let me on the show.

10:24.279 --> 10:25.864
[laughter]

10:25.864 --> 10:26.865
- So, I'm just gonna
throw that spring

10:26.865 --> 10:28.450
right into the forge.

10:28.450 --> 10:30.077
- It'll be interesting
how he's gonna

10:30.077 --> 10:31.578
uncoil the whole thing.
- Yeah, right.

10:31.578 --> 10:32.704
- Well, hopefully
he'll get it hot enough.

10:32.704 --> 10:33.997
We've seen so many smiths

10:33.997 --> 10:35.958
throw a spring into the forge

10:35.958 --> 10:38.502
pull it out lukewarm,
and then start banging on it.

10:38.502 --> 10:40.546
It's never gonna
straighten that way.

10:40.546 --> 10:42.548
<i>- The hardest part</i>
<i>of working with a coil spring</i>

10:42.548 --> 10:45.884
is gonna be
to unravel the spring.

10:45.884 --> 10:48.470
You got a guy
that's a 140 pounds,

10:48.470 --> 10:50.597
<i>trying to straighten</i>
<i>this piece out.</i>

10:50.597 --> 10:52.432
It ain't an easy task.

10:52.432 --> 10:54.059
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:54.059 --> 10:55.936
- See, there we go.
- Not hot enough.

10:55.936 --> 10:57.646
- [groans]
- Not hot enough.

10:57.646 --> 10:59.898
A gray spring will
not uncoil very well.

10:59.898 --> 11:01.275
<i>- Crap.</i>

11:01.275 --> 11:03.318
I can't turn nothing.

11:03.318 --> 11:04.695
<i>I can't even budge it.</i>

11:04.695 --> 11:06.989
- Put all your weight into it!

11:06.989 --> 11:08.824
Oh wait, he just did.

11:08.824 --> 11:10.534
<i>- It's time to go back</i>
<i>to The Forge,</i>

11:10.534 --> 11:12.786
heat it up again, retry.

11:12.786 --> 11:15.122
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:15.122 --> 11:16.748
<i>[country rock music]</i>

11:16.748 --> 11:19.084
- Brian just went over
to the grinder.

11:19.084 --> 11:20.669
Looks like he's planning on

11:20.669 --> 11:22.212
taking the teeth
off of those rasps.

11:22.212 --> 11:24.339
- What he's doing
is smart work because

11:24.339 --> 11:27.175
if he takes the teeth
off of the insides of two,

11:27.175 --> 11:29.052
and both sides
of the center one,

11:29.052 --> 11:31.013
that should forge weld
really nicely together.

11:31.013 --> 11:33.557
<i>- I would've preferred</i>
<i>to get a steel that</i>

11:33.557 --> 11:35.601
<i>I could just make</i>
<i>a knife directly</i>

11:35.601 --> 11:37.561
versus having to forge weld.

11:37.561 --> 11:40.480
<i>My forge welding</i>
<i>is hit and miss.</i>

11:40.480 --> 11:43.317
I've been about 50/50
on doing them in the past,

11:43.317 --> 11:47.571
so I'm pretty nervous about
putting the rasps together.

11:47.571 --> 11:49.823
I don't wanna
mess that weld up.

11:49.823 --> 11:52.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:52.117 --> 11:56.371
- My plan for this round
is to attempt a forge weld

11:56.371 --> 11:58.248
<i>and a spring steel together.</i>

11:58.248 --> 12:00.250
- 5160.

12:00.250 --> 12:01.960
It wants to be really
clean when the weld's up.

12:01.960 --> 12:04.755
If it's not clean, you've
got forge scale on there.

12:04.755 --> 12:07.424
- I am gonna take this steel
and I'm gonna pound it

12:07.424 --> 12:09.593
and press it
and I'll fold it up

12:09.593 --> 12:11.428
and crumple it into
a little ball if I have to

12:11.428 --> 12:13.513
to make a steel blade.

12:13.513 --> 12:15.515
<i>"Forged in Fire" is the</i>
<i>only show television show</i>

12:15.515 --> 12:18.393
<i>that has its own slot</i>
<i>at my house.</i>

12:18.393 --> 12:20.520
There is nothing else
that's allowed to be on TV

12:20.520 --> 12:22.230
when "Forged in Fire" is on.

12:22.230 --> 12:24.024
Easy on her.
Me and her are going out.

12:24.024 --> 12:26.193
- [laughs]

12:26.193 --> 12:28.570
<i>I'm gonna flatten the</i>
<i>lawnmower blades out first</i>

12:28.570 --> 12:31.073
and then cut them
into smaller pieces

12:31.073 --> 12:32.866
and then try to forge
weld those together.

12:32.866 --> 12:35.869
- Joey's going full-ham
with big blue.

12:35.869 --> 12:39.164
That's a lot of power
coming down with every strike.

12:39.164 --> 12:40.916
- And the fact that
you could hear it so much

12:40.916 --> 12:42.876
means that what
he's hammering is pretty thin.

12:42.876 --> 12:45.212
- I haven't done a whole lot
of forge welding,

12:45.212 --> 12:47.714
so I just don't know
if I'll be able to do it.

12:47.714 --> 12:49.633
- You know what I respect?

12:49.633 --> 12:52.469
Despite their
relative inexperience,

12:52.469 --> 12:54.680
each one of these smiths

12:54.680 --> 12:58.558
felt like they could come
into this arena and compete.

12:58.558 --> 13:00.727
<i>- I've had</i>
<i>a lot of professions.</i>

13:00.727 --> 13:03.146
I've been a professional Santa
Claus in the Christmas season.

13:03.146 --> 13:04.356
<i>I've been a clown.</i>

13:04.356 --> 13:06.274
Joe-bo the hobo.

13:06.274 --> 13:08.485
<i>Also was</i>
<i>a professional wrestler.</i>

13:08.485 --> 13:10.779
First started wrestling
as The German Headhunter.

13:10.779 --> 13:12.280
<i>And finally</i>
<i>I went to calling myself</i>

13:12.280 --> 13:14.116
<i>The God Chaser, Lex Hunter.</i>

13:14.116 --> 13:17.119
I just like making people
happy and entertaining.

13:17.119 --> 13:19.162
- One hour has elapsed!

13:19.162 --> 13:22.416
You only have two hours
remaining to finish your work!

13:22.416 --> 13:25.585
- I was struggling with
the spring to begin with

13:25.585 --> 13:28.088
but I got it somewhat straight.

13:28.088 --> 13:32.884
Since I got this straight rod,
I feel pretty confident

13:32.884 --> 13:35.595
<i>and I know I have plenty</i>
<i>of time to flatten that out</i>

13:35.595 --> 13:37.389
and make a blade.

13:37.389 --> 13:39.725
I think I might have time
to sit down and eat.

13:39.725 --> 13:41.977
- Tyler is starting
to fuller that steel out.

13:41.977 --> 13:44.688
- Fullering--you're gonna
push that blade out this way.

13:44.688 --> 13:47.107
You can actually get
about a three-inch blade

13:47.107 --> 13:49.568
out of a one-inch
piece of steel.

13:49.568 --> 13:52.195
<i>- I pace myself.</i>
<i>I don't get in a hurry.</i>

13:52.195 --> 13:54.448
I don't start running around
and acting crazy.

13:54.448 --> 13:56.241
<i>I'm not worried about time.</i>

13:56.241 --> 13:58.493
Never am worried
about the time.

13:58.493 --> 14:00.620
<i>My boss man's</i>
<i>worried about the time,</i>

14:00.620 --> 14:02.748
because he say I don't
get to work on time,

14:02.748 --> 14:06.460
but oh well.
[laughs]

14:06.460 --> 14:08.879
<i>- I'm feeling really good.</i>

14:08.879 --> 14:11.214
Hopefully, you know,
all the welds stick.

14:11.214 --> 14:14.092
- Brian--setting his
forge weld by hand.

14:14.092 --> 14:15.844
With a hammer.

14:15.844 --> 14:17.429
Taking his time.

14:17.429 --> 14:20.307
- He definitely has
a firm understanding

14:20.307 --> 14:22.225
of what he is doing.

14:22.225 --> 14:24.644
<i>- My son and I love the show.</i>

14:24.644 --> 14:27.647
And right around the time
my son was 11,

14:27.647 --> 14:29.608
<i>I decided that I needed to</i>

14:29.608 --> 14:31.276
<i>start finding things</i>
<i>for us to do together.</i>

14:31.276 --> 14:32.652
I said,
why don't we build ourselves

14:32.652 --> 14:34.404
<i>our own hunting knives?</i>

14:34.404 --> 14:35.781
Next thing you know,
we're buying metal and

14:35.781 --> 14:38.074
<i>starting to make knives.</i>

14:38.074 --> 14:40.410
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:40.410 --> 14:42.996
<i>- I'm very aware</i>
<i>of my surroundings.</i>

14:42.996 --> 14:44.623
I'm looking at Brian thinking,

14:44.623 --> 14:47.375
<i>"Man, his blade</i>
<i>looks awesome."</i>

14:47.375 --> 14:50.587
And I've got a pile of crap
sitting here in front of me.

14:50.587 --> 14:52.964
That's not good.

14:52.964 --> 14:56.092
Nothing is sticking.
It's turning into a fan.

14:56.092 --> 14:57.844
<i>Just spreading</i>
<i>away from itself.</i>

14:57.844 --> 15:00.305
- Matt's blade
has not welded at all.

15:00.305 --> 15:02.098
Nothing's binding up.

15:02.098 --> 15:04.476
That metal's just too dirty
to weld together.

15:04.476 --> 15:06.311
<i>- I'm squashing</i>
<i>this billet out,</i>

15:06.311 --> 15:09.689
and I can't get it to do
what I want it to do.

15:09.689 --> 15:13.235
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.235 --> 15:15.153
<i>- I'm starting to get</i>
<i>real frustrated because</i>

15:15.153 --> 15:18.365
my billet is not welding.

15:18.365 --> 15:19.950
<i>It's coming apart.</i>

15:19.950 --> 15:21.493
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what I'm gonna do.</i>

15:21.493 --> 15:24.120
I'm starting
to go into panic mode.

15:24.120 --> 15:26.122
<i>So, I'm gonna try again.</i>

15:26.122 --> 15:28.792
Just use a different approach.

15:28.792 --> 15:32.003
- I've got no idea
what Joey's doing.

15:32.003 --> 15:34.381
<i>- I'm gonna take and</i>
<i>fold one of them blades</i>

15:34.381 --> 15:35.674
<i>and try to forge weld</i>
<i>it together.</i>

15:35.674 --> 15:36.716
Like a taco.

15:38.802 --> 15:40.595
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:40.595 --> 15:42.430
- Matt's billet opened up
again.

15:42.430 --> 15:44.599
- Opened up, yeah.
- Forge weld is not taking.

15:44.599 --> 15:46.977
<i>- I don't think that</i>
<i>I am getting anywhere</i>

15:46.977 --> 15:48.395
<i>with this billet.</i>

15:48.395 --> 15:50.021
What am I gonna do?

15:50.021 --> 15:51.439
- Oh no, not the press.

15:51.439 --> 15:52.482
It's not gonna
do what you want.

15:52.482 --> 15:54.568
- Ahh.

15:54.568 --> 15:56.987
<i>- I'm most nervous about</i>

15:56.987 --> 15:58.572
<i>not being able</i>
<i>to complete the challenge</i>

15:58.572 --> 16:00.407
and turning in
some type of blade

16:00.407 --> 16:02.325
that's presentable
to the judges.

16:02.325 --> 16:03.910
- He never really took the time

16:03.910 --> 16:05.620
to get that forge scale
cleaned off

16:05.620 --> 16:07.581
after his first
attempt at welding.

16:07.581 --> 16:09.624
Now he's just pushing that
forge scale back on itself

16:09.624 --> 16:11.293
every single time.

16:11.293 --> 16:13.628
It just won't stick.

16:13.628 --> 16:16.381
- The same can be said
of Joey's billet as well.

16:16.381 --> 16:18.508
He's not forge welding.

16:18.508 --> 16:20.594
<i>- My first attempt</i>
<i>at forge welding didn't work.</i>

16:20.594 --> 16:24.431
My second attempt
at folding it didn't work.

16:24.431 --> 16:26.308
I don't know what
I'm gonna do at this point.

16:26.308 --> 16:29.185
- We might be down
to two after the first round.

16:29.185 --> 16:31.771
<i>- I'm very nervous that</i>
<i>I'm not gonna be able to</i>

16:31.771 --> 16:34.149
get something that I can turn
in in this amount of time.

16:34.149 --> 16:36.234
It doesn't look
too good right now.

16:39.821 --> 16:41.823
<i>- From watching</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire,"</i>

16:41.823 --> 16:45.076
I know that forge welding
never goes as planned.

16:45.076 --> 16:48.788
<i>So, I purposely saved</i>
<i>some of the leaf springs</i>

16:48.788 --> 16:52.125
so I would have it
just in case I needed it.

16:52.125 --> 16:54.336
<i>I lopped the end</i>
<i>of this billet off</i>

16:54.336 --> 16:56.129
and stick it on the
end of the anvil

16:56.129 --> 16:57.839
and I'm gonna
straighten it out.

16:57.839 --> 16:59.758
- Matt is just gonna
incorporate the stick

16:59.758 --> 17:02.427
right onto the side
of his piece of steel.

17:02.427 --> 17:04.888
<i>- I'm very nervous that</i>
<i>I'm not gonna be able to</i>

17:04.888 --> 17:07.974
get something that I can turn
in in this amount of time.

17:07.974 --> 17:11.645
<i>I still have a piece</i>
<i>of lawnmower blade left,</i>

17:11.645 --> 17:14.189
<i>so I just decided to split</i>
<i>it down through the holes</i>

17:14.189 --> 17:17.150
and use half
of that piece of blade

17:17.150 --> 17:18.443
<i>to make my knife.</i>

17:18.443 --> 17:19.903
<i>This'll work better because</i>

17:19.903 --> 17:21.571
I'm not trying to forge weld

17:21.571 --> 17:23.239
two pieces of metal together.

17:23.239 --> 17:24.991
<i>It's just one solid</i>
<i>piece of steel.</i>

17:24.991 --> 17:26.701
- Does Joey have enough steel?

17:26.701 --> 17:29.371
From here, it looks lean.

17:29.371 --> 17:31.957
- You have
45 minutes remaining!

17:31.957 --> 17:33.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:33.500 --> 17:35.460
Tyler's in the quench.

17:35.460 --> 17:38.922
- After the quench,
I'm pretty much done.

17:38.922 --> 17:41.007
I guess I'll just
hop on the grinder and

17:41.007 --> 17:43.176
make it at least look like
I'm doing something

17:43.176 --> 17:45.262
<i>like I do</i>
<i>at work most of the time.</i>

17:45.262 --> 17:47.973
Just touch my knife
to it every now and then.

17:47.973 --> 17:49.432
- [laughing] He's good.

17:49.432 --> 17:51.518
- Interesting technique.
- Yeah.

17:51.518 --> 17:54.771
- If you're out of steps,
find a treadmill.

17:54.771 --> 17:57.440
You ain't gonna go nowhere
but at least you're moving.

17:57.440 --> 17:59.859
[laughs]

17:59.859 --> 18:02.112
<i>- Steels quench</i>
<i>a little differently,</i>

18:02.112 --> 18:05.323
and as a novice, I'm not
super knowledgeable about

18:05.323 --> 18:08.034
what challenges there are
with quenching a file.

18:08.034 --> 18:10.787
- Brian--he's doing some
normalizing to his blade,

18:10.787 --> 18:12.372
and he's done a few cycles now.

18:12.372 --> 18:14.958
We should be seeing him
quench fairly soon.

18:14.958 --> 18:17.460
- I'm normalizing it
so when you heat treat,

18:17.460 --> 18:19.879
you get better blade
and better steel.

18:19.879 --> 18:21.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:21.798 --> 18:24.592
- All right, Brian quenched.

18:24.592 --> 18:26.428
- Aww, man.

18:26.428 --> 18:28.054
<i>Of course,</i>
<i>it's a little warped.</i>

18:28.054 --> 18:29.431
- Yeah,
he's got plenty of time.

18:29.431 --> 18:31.182
Just put it back in the forge.

18:31.182 --> 18:32.976
Do it again.

18:32.976 --> 18:35.562
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:35.562 --> 18:37.063
- Matt's made a real comeback.

18:37.063 --> 18:39.024
He's got a nice shape
out there.

18:39.024 --> 18:41.860
<i>- Now that I've got a blade,</i>
<i>I'm feeling good.</i>

18:41.860 --> 18:44.362
But now I have another dilemma.

18:44.362 --> 18:46.948
I got a hell of an inclusion
in the side of it

18:46.948 --> 18:50.994
from where I unrolled it and
had my holding rod welded back.

18:50.994 --> 18:53.330
Now I'm having a hell
of a time getting rid of it.

18:53.330 --> 18:55.874
<i>I've got a Dr. Jekyll</i>
<i>and Mr. Hyde blade.</i>

18:55.874 --> 18:58.043
The thing looks great
on one side,

18:58.043 --> 19:00.462
and it's ugly as sin
on the other side.

19:00.462 --> 19:02.756
<i>I'm hoping that</i>
<i>I can get this inclusion</i>

19:02.756 --> 19:05.216
ground down and make it look

19:05.216 --> 19:07.635
<i>like a blade</i>
<i>that's presentable.</i>

19:07.635 --> 19:09.554
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:09.554 --> 19:10.930
<i>- I hate this clock, man.</i>

19:10.930 --> 19:12.932
<i>It's about to drive me nuts.</i>

19:12.932 --> 19:16.311
I never thought three hours
could run by so fast.

19:16.311 --> 19:17.729
<i>It ain't nothing</i>
<i>like sitting at home</i>

19:17.729 --> 19:19.939
on your couch
watching it on TV.

19:19.939 --> 19:22.317
- Joey's got
an extremely thin blade.

19:22.317 --> 19:23.610
And when he goes
for that quench,

19:23.610 --> 19:25.445
if it doesn't warp like crazy,

19:25.445 --> 19:27.781
I'll be extremely surprised.

19:27.781 --> 19:30.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:30.367 --> 19:33.203
- Ten, nine, eight,

19:33.203 --> 19:36.206
seven, six, five,

19:36.206 --> 19:40.543
four, three, two, one!

19:40.543 --> 19:43.129
Bladesmiths, drop your tools!
Shut down your machines!

19:43.129 --> 19:44.756
This round is over.

19:44.756 --> 19:47.050
<i>[mellow music]</i>

19:47.050 --> 19:50.929
- The inclusion is my
biggest problem right now.

19:50.929 --> 19:53.681
<i>My hope is that one</i>
<i>of the other bladesmiths</i>

19:53.681 --> 19:55.975
didn't do quite as well.

19:55.975 --> 19:57.185
<i>[tense music]</i>

19:57.185 --> 19:58.978
- All right, bladesmiths,

19:58.978 --> 20:00.939
I know that was
an interesting first round.

20:00.939 --> 20:03.942
Not only did you have
to earn your spot at the anvil,

20:03.942 --> 20:05.985
you had to use mystery steel.

20:05.985 --> 20:08.988
Brian, please present
your work to the judges.

20:08.988 --> 20:10.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:10.949 --> 20:12.784
<i>- Well, Brian,</i>

20:12.784 --> 20:14.411
<i>I like how you set up</i>
<i>for that weld.</i>

20:14.411 --> 20:16.162
You did everything
that I would've done.

20:16.162 --> 20:18.081
That was good to watch.
It's pretty straight.

20:18.081 --> 20:19.999
There's a little kick
in the handle there,

20:19.999 --> 20:22.043
<i>but that could be corrected.</i>

20:22.043 --> 20:23.420
Overall, very well done.

20:23.420 --> 20:25.296
- Thank you.

20:25.296 --> 20:27.465
- Tyler, please present
your blade to the judges.

20:27.465 --> 20:29.717
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:29.717 --> 20:31.511
<i>- When you got on big blue,</i>
<i>originally you started</i>

20:31.511 --> 20:33.555
<i>stretching this out</i>
<i>the long way,</i>

20:33.555 --> 20:35.140
But what I liked seeing was
you finally got it sideways

20:35.140 --> 20:36.975
and started fullering
this material out.

20:36.975 --> 20:38.685
Good move on that.

20:38.685 --> 20:40.687
Your handle's got
a nice length through it,

20:40.687 --> 20:42.772
<i>but it gets a little lean</i>
<i>towards that back end.</i>

20:42.772 --> 20:44.399
But all in all, good job.

20:44.399 --> 20:46.276
- Thank you.

20:46.276 --> 20:48.111
- Matt, please present
your blade to the judges.

20:48.111 --> 20:50.363
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:50.363 --> 20:51.865
<i>- The issues I have</i>
<i>with this is</i>

20:51.865 --> 20:54.117
you have all this
scarring right here.

20:54.117 --> 20:56.035
<i>It's got a big potato chip</i>
<i>over there.</i>

20:56.035 --> 20:57.829
So, what is the
structural integrity

20:57.829 --> 20:59.664
when you're trying
to hit with this?

20:59.664 --> 21:01.624
If you do move forward,
it's gonna be an issue

21:01.624 --> 21:04.294
of what and how much you can
do to this metal right here

21:04.294 --> 21:06.337
before it starts
to weaken the blade itself.

21:06.337 --> 21:08.923
But overall,
you did turn in a blade.

21:08.923 --> 21:10.967
Thank you.
- You're welcome.

21:10.967 --> 21:12.594
- All right, Joey,

21:12.594 --> 21:13.887
please present
your blade to the judges.

21:13.887 --> 21:15.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:15.930 --> 21:18.725
<i>- Well, Joey, this is</i>
<i>a very, very thin blade.</i>

21:18.725 --> 21:20.643
I mean, I would be
kind of nervous

21:20.643 --> 21:22.103
to chop into bones
with something like this.

21:22.103 --> 21:24.898
There's some
complex warp in it.

21:24.898 --> 21:27.484
<i>Sort of S-shaped</i>
<i>as you go down the blade.</i>

21:27.484 --> 21:29.319
I know you were working
at the last minute

21:29.319 --> 21:31.154
trying to do something

21:31.154 --> 21:33.490
and I really applaud you
for turning in this knife.

21:33.490 --> 21:35.533
- I wasn't gonna give up.

21:35.533 --> 21:37.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:37.952 --> 21:41.289
- Gentlemen, the judges have
reached a final decision.

21:41.289 --> 21:42.916
It's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

21:42.916 --> 21:45.877
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:45.877 --> 21:47.587
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:47.587 --> 21:50.256
Joey, your blade
did not make the cut.

21:50.256 --> 21:51.716
- Joey, though you had trouble

21:51.716 --> 21:53.218
with your forge
in the beginning,

21:53.218 --> 21:54.969
you managed to put
a blade together,

21:54.969 --> 21:56.888
and that's something
to be proud of.

21:56.888 --> 21:58.431
<i>Unfortunately,</i>
<i>that blade is extremely thin</i>

21:58.431 --> 22:00.433
<i>and has an S curve to it.</i>

22:00.433 --> 22:03.061
We don't feel you can
fix that in the second round.

22:03.061 --> 22:04.729
- Understood.

22:04.729 --> 22:07.065
- Joey,
please surrender your weapon.

22:07.065 --> 22:08.983
<i>- I'm disappointed</i>
<i>I didn't make it,</i>

22:08.983 --> 22:10.777
<i>but it was an honor</i>
<i>to be here.</i>

22:10.777 --> 22:12.570
I had more fun doing this

22:12.570 --> 22:14.364
than I did when
I was a pro wrestler

22:14.364 --> 22:16.157
<i>because you don't</i>
<i>have to worry about</i>

22:16.157 --> 22:18.409
getting hit in the head
with a chair.

22:18.409 --> 22:19.744
<i>It was way more enjoyable.</i>

22:19.744 --> 22:22.330
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:22.330 --> 22:24.165
- All right, bladesmiths,

22:24.165 --> 22:25.458
congratulations,
you made it to the second round

22:25.458 --> 22:27.210
of this competition.

22:27.210 --> 22:29.045
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

22:29.045 --> 22:30.630
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons

22:30.630 --> 22:32.715
by attaching handles to them.

22:32.715 --> 22:35.552
You will have three hours
in which to complete your work.

22:35.552 --> 22:36.928
Good luck.

22:36.928 --> 22:39.305
Your three hours starts now.

22:39.305 --> 22:41.474
<i>[rock music]</i>

22:41.474 --> 22:43.643
- Explosive start.
Oh.

22:43.643 --> 22:47.522
- Which smith has the most
work to do right now?

22:47.522 --> 22:49.023
- Either Matt or Tyler.

22:49.023 --> 22:50.608
Tyler's really got
a beefy blade.

22:50.608 --> 22:52.402
Could use some profiling.

22:52.402 --> 22:54.862
- It feels good to be able
to make round two,

22:54.862 --> 22:57.574
but I already knew that
I was gonna make round two.

22:57.574 --> 22:59.200
<i>It wasn't like a shocker.</i>

22:59.200 --> 23:00.702
<i>I knew before I even came here</i>

23:00.702 --> 23:02.787
<i>I was gonna make round two.</i>

23:02.787 --> 23:05.290
<i>If you can't put a handle</i>
<i>on in three hours,</i>

23:05.290 --> 23:07.750
<i>either you ain't got nothing</i>
<i>to make a handle out of</i>

23:07.750 --> 23:10.128
or you just don't even deserve

23:10.128 --> 23:12.255
to be making a knife
in the first place.

23:12.255 --> 23:14.173
I'm about to go with
something fancy-looking.

23:14.173 --> 23:16.551
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:16.551 --> 23:18.928
<i>- First thing I do is try</i>
<i>and look for a wood,</i>

23:18.928 --> 23:21.014
because it's easy to work with.

23:21.014 --> 23:23.558
<i>My plan is to just get</i>
<i>a handle fitted,</i>

23:23.558 --> 23:25.518
<i>and then it's just</i>

23:25.518 --> 23:27.395
<i>finishing it to make</i>
<i>it look nice, I guess.</i>

23:27.395 --> 23:29.230
<i>I don't know,</i>
<i>maybe I'll have a break time.</i>

23:29.230 --> 23:31.482
Maybe I can get
some ice cream.

23:31.482 --> 23:33.776
- My biggest concern right now

23:33.776 --> 23:36.029
is get that structure fixed up

23:36.029 --> 23:37.780
so it'll pass a bone chop.

23:37.780 --> 23:39.365
- Does that blade have a shot

23:39.365 --> 23:41.200
in this competition
against those bones?

23:41.200 --> 23:43.411
- Yep.
- Yeah.

23:43.411 --> 23:45.413
<i>- I've been thinking about</i>
<i>the inclusion in my blade,</i>

23:45.413 --> 23:48.875
but I'm concerned about
actually heating that blade up.

23:48.875 --> 23:53.630
So, I'm gonna take epoxy and
mix it with some powdered steel

23:53.630 --> 23:56.507
to kind of mimic
making a liquid steel

23:56.507 --> 23:58.217
<i>to put on the side</i>
<i>of my blade.</i>

23:58.217 --> 23:59.385
- I like that.

23:59.385 --> 24:00.970
I know you love it, Dave.

24:00.970 --> 24:01.971
- It's great.
- I know you love it.

24:01.971 --> 24:03.264
It's a work-around.

24:03.264 --> 24:04.891
- The only issue I have is that

24:04.891 --> 24:06.893
the shock from
hitting those bones--

24:06.893 --> 24:09.562
I mean, it could just pop that
epoxy right off the side.

24:09.562 --> 24:11.314
- One hour has elapsed.

24:11.314 --> 24:12.690
That means you have
two hours remaining

24:12.690 --> 24:14.108
to finish your work.

24:14.108 --> 24:16.027
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:16.027 --> 24:17.945
<i>- I got my handle</i>
<i>glued together nice.</i>

24:17.945 --> 24:19.364
<i>It feels good in the hand.</i>

24:19.364 --> 24:21.282
The next step is sharpening.

24:21.282 --> 24:24.285
- Brian is working on
a very slow grinder over there.

24:24.285 --> 24:26.245
I wonder why he's
moving so slowly.

24:26.245 --> 24:30.249
I use a really low belt speed
so I don't burn anything.

24:30.249 --> 24:32.210
<i>I have plenty of time.</i>
<i>I'm not in a hurry.</i>

24:32.210 --> 24:35.421
Maybe I can start daydreaming
about golf or something.

24:35.421 --> 24:36.714
[laughs]

24:36.714 --> 24:38.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:38.383 --> 24:39.926
- You know what
a chick magnet is?

24:39.926 --> 24:42.845
I know a blade ain't a magnet,
but...

24:42.845 --> 24:45.306
If I was gonna chick,
I'd be all over that.

24:45.306 --> 24:47.225
I'm gonna win the $10,000.

24:47.225 --> 24:49.018
I already got it in the bag.

24:49.018 --> 24:52.939
I'm gonna spend
the $10,000 on stuff

24:52.939 --> 24:54.732
<i>to make more blades with.</i>

24:54.732 --> 24:58.236
And I might give
a dollar to my girlfriend.

24:58.236 --> 24:59.654
- How you making out?

24:59.654 --> 25:02.031
- I'm doing pretty good,
I think.

25:02.031 --> 25:04.992
- I think that I've made
an acceptable repair

25:04.992 --> 25:07.537
to the inclusion
on the side of my blade.

25:07.537 --> 25:10.998
So, now I need to get
a rock-solid handle on it.

25:10.998 --> 25:12.709
[clicking]

25:12.709 --> 25:14.293
- That is just
a funny sound coming from

25:14.293 --> 25:15.336
Matt's drill press over there.

25:15.336 --> 25:17.296
[clicking]

25:17.296 --> 25:18.673
[together]
Oh!

25:18.673 --> 25:19.799
- [whistles]

25:19.799 --> 25:22.093
Holy cow.

25:23.636 --> 25:24.929
- [whistles]

25:24.929 --> 25:25.972
- I got a cut.

25:25.972 --> 25:27.140
- That was his hand.

25:27.140 --> 25:29.308
- Holy cow.

25:29.308 --> 25:31.602
That's why you really wanna
see those blades in a vice.

25:31.602 --> 25:33.855
Too much of an edge on her.

25:33.855 --> 25:35.523
- It took a nice
chunk out of you.

25:35.523 --> 25:37.108
- This is the time in the shop

25:37.108 --> 25:38.609
where you have
to make that decision.

25:38.609 --> 25:40.278
Do you pack up
and go get stitches,

25:40.278 --> 25:42.280
or do you swipe
a man-aid on it,

25:42.280 --> 25:43.906
some paper towels and
duct tape and go back to work?

25:43.906 --> 25:45.575
- Yep.

25:45.575 --> 25:46.868
- I think we went
with man-aid solution.

25:46.868 --> 25:48.828
- There we go.
He's back at it.

25:48.828 --> 25:52.457
- You have just one hour
remaining to finish your work.

25:52.457 --> 25:54.041
I think Brian's done.

25:54.041 --> 25:56.127
He's grinning
like a 17-year-old kid

25:56.127 --> 25:57.628
at a rated R movie.

25:57.628 --> 25:58.755
- Fun, huh?

25:58.755 --> 26:00.548
- You all done?

26:00.548 --> 26:02.383
- I don't know what else
I would do right now.

26:02.383 --> 26:04.343
- It is a bit uncomfortable
sitting there

26:04.343 --> 26:06.137
<i>with time remaining.</i>

26:06.137 --> 26:08.848
But sometimes,
when things are so good,

26:08.848 --> 26:11.267
and you keep trying
to make them better,

26:11.267 --> 26:13.019
<i>it sometimes makes it worse.</i>

26:13.019 --> 26:16.022
- You didn't got tired
of working on yours?

26:16.022 --> 26:18.149
Brian--he finished
his blade early.

26:18.149 --> 26:20.151
<i>And he's just</i>
<i>sitting down on the job.</i>

26:20.151 --> 26:22.445
To me, that doesn't look right.

26:22.445 --> 26:24.864
If you're done, then
just act like you're doing it.

26:24.864 --> 26:26.657
<i>That's what I'm doing</i>
<i>with the judges here.</i>

26:26.657 --> 26:30.453
I'm pretending to be busy,
but...

26:30.453 --> 26:32.121
<i>I was just shaving.</i>

26:32.121 --> 26:33.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:33.164 --> 26:34.791
- I'm still alive!

26:34.791 --> 26:36.793
My hand has stopped bleeding.

26:36.793 --> 26:38.711
I'm not gonna bleed out.

26:38.711 --> 26:40.713
<i>But time is running out.</i>

26:40.713 --> 26:43.299
<i>I need to get</i>
<i>the edge on my blade.</i>

26:43.299 --> 26:44.967
Where'd everybody go?

26:44.967 --> 26:46.552
- Hey!

26:46.552 --> 26:48.262
<i>- We're back to business.</i>

26:48.262 --> 26:50.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:50.515 --> 26:52.433
- Five, four,

26:52.433 --> 26:55.978
three, two, one.

26:55.978 --> 26:58.523
This round is over.

26:58.523 --> 27:03.736
- My finished blade went
from being the ugly duckling

27:03.736 --> 27:05.780
<i>to the little engine</i>
<i>that could.</i>

27:05.780 --> 27:08.825
I think if my blade
makes it through the bones,

27:08.825 --> 27:11.035
<i>I have a chance.</i>

27:11.035 --> 27:13.663
- Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

27:13.663 --> 27:15.623
To test the strength
and durability of your edge,

27:15.623 --> 27:18.501
I'm gonna chop into
these bones six times each.

27:18.501 --> 27:20.044
This test is all about

27:20.044 --> 27:21.629
what the bones
do to your blades,

27:21.629 --> 27:23.005
and not what your blades
do to these bones.

27:23.005 --> 27:24.507
Brian, you're up first.

27:24.507 --> 27:25.591
- Swing hard.

27:25.591 --> 27:27.093
- I know no other way.

27:27.093 --> 27:28.636
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:28.636 --> 27:29.929
<i>- I'm just worried.</i>

27:29.929 --> 27:31.847
<i>They're pretty big bones,</i>

27:31.847 --> 27:34.267
<i>and anybody that watches</i>
<i>this show knows that</i>

27:34.267 --> 27:36.185
edge damage or blade breakage

27:36.185 --> 27:38.563
gets you sent home
pretty quick.

27:38.563 --> 27:41.482
<i>[grunge rock music]</i>

27:41.482 --> 27:47.863
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:47.863 --> 27:49.240
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:49.240 --> 27:51.200
- Well, Brian,

27:51.200 --> 27:52.660
your edge held up perfectly.

27:52.660 --> 27:54.412
- Awesome.

27:54.412 --> 27:55.788
- Other than a whole lot
of bone dust on here,

27:55.788 --> 27:57.707
I don't see any issue
with the edge.

27:57.707 --> 27:59.792
Still seems very sharp.

27:59.792 --> 28:01.669
Very well done.
- Thank you.

28:01.669 --> 28:03.296
- Matt, you're up next.
Are you ready?

28:03.296 --> 28:04.755
- I'm as ready as I'm gonna be.

28:04.755 --> 28:07.133
- All right.

28:07.133 --> 28:09.802
<i>- Bone is nasty.</i>

28:09.802 --> 28:12.930
I'm nervous about
the epoxy I put on the blade.

28:12.930 --> 28:14.932
<i>I'm just hoping</i>
<i>this knife's gonna hold.</i>

28:14.932 --> 28:16.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:16.976 --> 28:19.937
<i>[rock music]</i>

28:19.937 --> 28:25.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:25.985 --> 28:27.111
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:27.111 --> 28:28.654
- Well, Matt,

28:28.654 --> 28:30.406
the epoxy stayed on.

28:30.406 --> 28:33.117
[laughter]
- Good deal.

28:33.117 --> 28:35.661
- There's some chipping that
happened up here at the edge.

28:35.661 --> 28:37.872
But the whole thing
held together.

28:37.872 --> 28:40.041
Well done.
- Thank you.

28:40.041 --> 28:42.209
- Tyler, you're up.
You ready?

28:42.209 --> 28:44.295
- I wanna do it,
but I'm ready.

28:44.295 --> 28:46.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:46.464 --> 28:49.091
<i>I think that my knife</i>
<i>is gonna destroy the bone.</i>

28:49.091 --> 28:51.344
<i>Fragments are gonna</i>
<i>fly everywhere.</i>

28:51.344 --> 28:53.304
<i>I'd swing at those</i>
<i>bones till either</i>

28:53.304 --> 28:55.264
I broke down,
or the blade broke down.

28:55.264 --> 28:57.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:57.558 --> 29:00.519
<i>[rock music]</i>

29:00.519 --> 29:05.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:05.941 --> 29:08.402
I was hoping it would
cut all the way through it.

29:08.402 --> 29:09.403
- [laughs]

29:09.403 --> 29:11.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:11.405 --> 29:13.574
- Well, Tyler,

29:13.574 --> 29:15.576
there is some chipping along
the blade here from the bone.

29:15.576 --> 29:20.081
And the handle is very round.

29:20.081 --> 29:23.125
It just wasn't super duper
comfortable in my hand.

29:23.125 --> 29:25.169
But overall, well done.

29:25.169 --> 29:26.587
- Appreciate it. Thank you.

29:26.587 --> 29:28.047
- Up next
is the sharpness test,

29:28.047 --> 29:28.964
and for that
I give you to Dave.

29:28.964 --> 29:31.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:31.300 --> 29:32.927
- All right, gentlemen,

29:32.927 --> 29:34.679
to test the sharpness
of your blade,

29:34.679 --> 29:36.263
I'll be slicing into
those ropes three times.

29:36.263 --> 29:37.598
Brian you're up first.
Are you ready?

29:37.598 --> 29:38.557
- Let's go.

29:38.557 --> 29:39.517
- Okay.

29:41.143 --> 29:44.105
<i>[rock music]</i>

29:44.105 --> 29:49.527
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:49.527 --> 29:51.112
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:51.112 --> 29:53.739
All right, Brian,
it's a very sharp blade.

29:53.739 --> 29:56.367
And it cut the rope
pretty cleanly.

29:56.367 --> 29:58.119
But it wasn't able
to cut very deeply

29:58.119 --> 30:01.330
because that edge geometry
is very stout.

30:01.330 --> 30:02.832
As far as the feel goes,

30:02.832 --> 30:04.417
it's a little bit square

30:04.417 --> 30:06.085
on the back
of the handle right here.

30:06.085 --> 30:08.254
It'd be nice to see
that rounded over.

30:08.254 --> 30:09.964
But it's definitely a cutter.

30:09.964 --> 30:11.298
- Thank you.

30:11.298 --> 30:12.925
- Matt, you ready?

30:12.925 --> 30:14.468
- Let's put it on the floor.
- Okay.

30:14.468 --> 30:17.430
<i>[grungy electronic music]</i>

30:17.430 --> 30:24.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:24.311 --> 30:25.730
- Yes.

30:25.730 --> 30:27.606
- Good job.

30:27.606 --> 30:31.444
- This fix you came up with
was ingenious.

30:31.444 --> 30:33.279
- I call that epoxy Damascus.

30:33.279 --> 30:34.613
- [laughs]

30:34.613 --> 30:36.866
Your edge is extremely sharp.

30:36.866 --> 30:39.201
I mean, you can see
it's cleanly cut.

30:39.201 --> 30:40.161
[chuckling]
Nicely done.

30:40.161 --> 30:41.162
- Thank you.

30:41.162 --> 30:42.621
- Tyler, you ready?

30:42.621 --> 30:44.123
- Yeah, I'm ready.
- Okay.

30:45.916 --> 30:48.919
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:48.919 --> 30:55.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:55.593 --> 30:57.219
<i>[tense music]</i>

30:57.219 --> 30:58.804
Tyler, as you can see,

30:58.804 --> 31:00.431
your rope--it's cut.

31:00.431 --> 31:02.183
The issue I have
is with this handle.

31:02.183 --> 31:04.769
I had to adjust
after every hit.

31:04.769 --> 31:07.855
Every time I hit, that knife
would roll in my hand.

31:07.855 --> 31:10.316
There's just
no contouring to it.

31:10.316 --> 31:12.610
It makes for a very
difficult knife to control.

31:12.610 --> 31:15.196
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:15.196 --> 31:17.573
- Bladesmiths, the judges have
completed their deliberation

31:17.573 --> 31:19.325
and they've made
a final decision.

31:19.325 --> 31:21.494
It's time for
another elimination.

31:21.494 --> 31:23.996
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

31:23.996 --> 31:25.706
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:25.706 --> 31:29.293
Tyler, your blade
did not make the cut.

31:29.293 --> 31:31.962
- Tyler, we've always
said that the handle

31:31.962 --> 31:34.673
is what connects
the end user to the blade.

31:34.673 --> 31:36.675
Your handle was a little
bit on the cylindrical side,

31:36.675 --> 31:38.803
<i>which makes it hard</i>
<i>to hold on to.</i>

31:38.803 --> 31:41.388
And your blade took
some damage and it just

31:41.388 --> 31:43.557
wasn't as sharp as
that of your competitors.

31:43.557 --> 31:46.352
For those reasons,
we have to let you go.

31:46.352 --> 31:49.396
- All right, Tyler,
please surrender your blade.

31:49.396 --> 31:52.441
<i>- The damage that was</i>
<i>done from the bone--</i>

31:52.441 --> 31:54.193
it dulled the piss out of it.

31:54.193 --> 31:58.739
But I've learned more
in the past few hours

31:58.739 --> 32:01.492
<i>than I have since</i>
<i>I've started bladesmithing.</i>

32:01.492 --> 32:03.285
And I believe it will make me

32:03.285 --> 32:05.371
a better bladesmith
in the future.

32:05.371 --> 32:08.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:08.916 --> 32:10.918
- Bladesmiths, congratulations,

32:10.918 --> 32:12.837
you've made it to the final
round of this competition.

32:12.837 --> 32:14.505
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

32:14.505 --> 32:16.340
to recreate an iconic
weapon from history.

32:16.340 --> 32:18.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:18.968 --> 32:22.972
The war golok.

32:22.972 --> 32:25.933
<i>Originating in the Philippines</i>
<i>during the 16th century,</i>

32:25.933 --> 32:27.476
<i>the war golok</i>
<i>featured a straight,</i>

32:27.476 --> 32:29.270
<i>double-edged blade</i>
<i>with no tip.</i>

32:29.270 --> 32:31.230
<i>Due to the Spanish</i>
<i>occupation at the time,</i>

32:31.230 --> 32:33.482
<i>Filipinos were outlawed</i>
<i>from having pointed swords</i>

32:33.482 --> 32:35.693
<i>and the blade was</i>
<i>often used for vegetation</i>

32:35.693 --> 32:37.778
<i>and chopping wood.</i>

32:37.778 --> 32:40.155
<i>However, by the</i>
<i>Philippine Revolution in 1896,</i>

32:40.155 --> 32:42.533
<i>Filipinos adapted</i>
<i>to the tipless weapon</i>

32:42.533 --> 32:44.201
<i>and it became a weapon of war.</i>

32:44.201 --> 32:46.287
<i>It was so effective in battle,</i>

32:46.287 --> 32:48.372
<i>it inspired later variations</i>
<i>of the weapon such as</i>

32:48.372 --> 32:53.043
<i>the British military's</i>
<i>army golok in the early 1950s.</i>

32:53.043 --> 32:56.797
The blade must be double-edged
and have a fuller on each side

32:56.797 --> 32:58.299
and no tip.

32:58.299 --> 33:01.552
- War golok?
Never heard of it.

33:01.552 --> 33:05.180
<i>But I have no fear in it.</i>
<i>It's a nice, straight sword.</i>

33:05.180 --> 33:07.057
<i>Stuff that's in my wheelhouse.</i>

33:07.057 --> 33:08.517
I think I'm gonna nail it

33:08.517 --> 33:09.977
as long as I don't
cut a finger off

33:09.977 --> 33:12.062
sharpening
both sides of it.

33:12.062 --> 33:13.898
- Bladesmiths, you will have
five days at your home forge

33:13.898 --> 33:15.357
to complete this challenge.

33:15.357 --> 33:17.484
After five days,
you will return

33:17.484 --> 33:20.195
and present your war goloks
to our panel of expert judges.

33:20.195 --> 33:22.197
And only after
they've brutally tested them

33:22.197 --> 33:24.491
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

33:24.491 --> 33:26.577
and hand you
that check for ten grand.

33:26.577 --> 33:29.538
Good luck, bladesmiths,
we'll see you in five days.

33:29.538 --> 33:33.083
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:33.083 --> 33:35.920
- After battling my way
through all the competition,

33:35.920 --> 33:40.174
it is surreal to be making
a blade at my home forge.

33:40.174 --> 33:42.009
<i>I've had to lengthen my forge,</i>

33:42.009 --> 33:44.011
<i>I've had to make</i>
<i>some equipment</i>

33:44.011 --> 33:46.639
just to do this challenge
